**Person-- George Leslie Mackay**
George Leslie Mackay was the first Presbyterian missionary to northern Formosa during the Qing era. Mackay was born in Oxford County, Canada West, Canada. Commissioned by the Canada Presbyterian Church, Mackay arrived at Tamsui, northern Formosa in 1872, and lived there until his death in 1901. To preached his gospel messages, he learned vernacular Taiwanese fluently from local herds boys. At first, Mackay was an itinerant dentistry who practiced amongst the lowland aborigines, and he was often labeled as a ‘foreign devil’ and a ‘black-bearded barbarian’. Afterward, he established churches, schools and a hospital practicing Western biomedicine. By 1888, he had 16 chapels and 500 converts among the native Taiwanese. Taiwan would not be what it is today without George Leslie Mackay’s lifetime dedication and his love to Taiwan.

