**As a Perfectionist**
	As a perfectionist, I always want to make everything perfect, no matter how much I need to pay for it. When I look at the imperfect part, I cannot help but feel painful instantly. And, to reach every too high goal I set for myself, it seems inevitable that I need to sacrifice something. For example, my health, some relationship, or other things I consider less important. However, ironically, many times, at last, those things I have sacrificed eventually strike back to me, making me fail at the things I want to do the best. At that time, I would usually tell myself:” It is all because you are not good enough, you should do more, you should be smarter.” Until recently, I read some essays about why we should keep our steps small but manageable; I finally realize the desire that I want to do things perfectly first, make me lose sight of one important truth: I can accomplish more if I work consistently in an imperfect way. Maybe I don’t need to sacrifice so many things in my life. What’s more, I found another truth: It is the unrealistic perfectionism makes me trap in unnecessary struggle and failure.



**[Week Seven]**
**What are some important qualities of a good (or bad) supervisor/boss**
It is important to choose a good supervisor, who can help us more successful in our career. In my opinion, a good supervisor should have great communication skills, treat his/her staffs fairly, and set a good example. First, it’s vital for good supervisors to make clear and understandable work instructions. If supervisors cannot make their desires clear, their employees will not know how to finish the tasks. Second, being fair is an essential trait of supervisors. When supervisors are able to treat their employees fairly, the employees will focus on working towards individual and group goals, instead of focusing on gamesmanship. Third, a good supervisor should set the example for her employees by her own attitude and behavior. If supervisors want their employees to be diligent, they should be diligent themselves. On the other hand, if supervisors say one thing and do another, the employees won’t trust them and won't follow them enthusiastically. In conclusion, I believe that treating the employee fairly, having good communication skills, and setting an example in front of the employee are important qualifications to be a good supervisor. 
 
